nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>The=
 World Without Time. </strong>If time doesn&#8217;t exist, how do we make s=
ense of this new, timeless world? Instead of a linear time, Rovelli offers =
in its place a &#8220;net of interconnected events, where the variables in =
play adhere to probabilistic rules.&#8221; Instead of time and objects, &#8=
220;There are only events and relations.&#8221;</p></li><li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 3.75px; margin-left: 7.5px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 3.75px;">=
<p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; =
margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>The Sources of Time. </strong>Ok ok cool BUT &#8=
230; evolution occurs, erosion reshapes landscapes, we experience time, we =
have memories of the past, we <em>can&#8217;t</em> remember the future. Whe=
re does the sense of time&#8217;s flow come from if time isn&#8217;t real? =
Rovelli offers up some explanations here based on the best thinking today. =
Ultimately, what we experience as time is &#8220;a multilayered, complex co=
ncept with multiple, distinct properties deriving from various different ap=
proximations.&#8221;&nbsp;</p></li></ol><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">This is trippy stuff.&nbsp=
;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 1em 0;">Whenever I fly, I have a cranberry vodka. I&#8217;m not sure =
why. I don&#8217;t drink cranberry vodka on the ground. But somehow, it&#82=
17;s become my plane drink. So earlier this month, I found myself 1.5 cranb=
erry vodkas deep on a flight, sitting aisle with Puja by the window and Dev=
 asleep in his carseat between us. And I was absolutely giddy.&nbsp;</p><p =
style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1e=
m 0;">At the risk of waking the baby and ruining the flight for us and ever=
yone around us, I kept passing my iPad over to Puja, watching her reaction =
expectantly as she read just-highlighted sections I pointed at, like this:&=
nbsp;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0=
;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>Dear reader, pause for a moment to let th=
is conclusion sink in. In my opinion, it is the <strong>most astounding con=
clusion arrived at in the whole of contemporary physics</strong>. It simply=
 makes no sense to ask which moment in the life of your sister on Proxima b=
 </em>[a planet far, far away]<em> corresponds to </em>now&#8230;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0=
; margin-left: 1em;"><em><strong>The notion of &#8220;the present&#8221; re=
fers to things that are close to us, not anything that is far away. Our &#8=
220;present&#8221; does not extend throughout the universe.</strong> It is =
like a bubble around us&#8230;</em></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em><stro=
ng>The idea that a well-defined </strong></em><strong>now </strong><em><str=
ong>exists throughout the universe is an illusion</strong>, an illegitimate=
 extrapolation of our own experience... The &#8220;present of the universe&=
#8221; is meaningless.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><strong>There is no un=
iversal now.</strong>&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">There&#8217;s not a moment that&#82=
17;s the same on a far away planet as the one you&#8217;re experiencing rig=
ht now &#8211; not as measured on a clock, just&#8230; at all. I, too, like=
 you might be right now, tried imagining it, and <em>of course </em>there&#=
8217;s a moment that&#8217;s happening now, there, even if we can&#8217;t a=
ccess it. But, apparently, there&#8217;s really not. According to Rovelli, =
asking what&#8217;s happening on Proxima b <em>now </em>is like me sitting =
in New York and wondering what&#8217;s happening in Beijing <em>here.&nbsp;=
</em></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 1em 0;">That&#8217;s just one of the five or six sections I passe=
d to Puja. Non-stop brain-melters.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The takeaway: <strong>=
there is no </strong><em><strong>one</strong></em><strong> time</strong>.&n=
bsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 1em 0;">Our experience of time is based on our perspective and rel=
ationship with the universe, and on our experience constantly living in the=
 present moment, sandwiched between memory and anticipation.</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In=
 other words,<strong> there is no time independent of us.</strong>&nbsp;</p=
